&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Looping statement &lt;strong&gt;WHILE&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;A list (00, 03, 04) corresponding to the parameter &amp;amp;EOR&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;%NITEMS&lt;/strong&gt; is a macro processor function that returns as its value the number of members in an argument list&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&amp;amp;EOR[&amp;amp;CTR]&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;keyword-macro-parameters&#34;&gt;&lt;a class=&#34;anchor&#34; href=&#34;#keyword-macro-parameters&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt; Keyword Macro Parameters&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;With positional parameters, if an argument is to be omitted, the macro invocation statement must contain a null argument (two consecutive commas) to maintain the correct argument positions&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;However, if a macro has a large number of parameters, and only a few of these are given values in a typical invocation, a different form of parameter specification is more useful
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Perhaps an entire operating system is to be generated from a macro invocation. In such cases, most of the parameters may have acceptable default values; the macro invocation specifies only the changes from the default set of values.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;GENER ,DIRECT,3&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;GENER TYPE=DIRECT, CHANGE=3&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;details&gt;&lt;summary&gt;Figure 4.10&lt;/summary&gt;&lt;div&gt;
